<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER CONFIDENCE UP SLIGHTLY IN APRIL: SURVEY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April 27 (CNA) 04/27/07  19:34:16 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's consumer confidence indicators increased slightly in
April, according to the results of a survey released Friday by
the National Central University's Research Center for Taiwan
Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
The consumer confidence index stood at 67.67 in April, up 0.55
points from the previous month, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
While five out of the six indicators used in the survey rose in
April, the "timing for investing in the stock market over the
next six months" indicator registering the greatest increase,
gaining 2.20 points from March to stand at 73.20.
</P>
<P>
Coming in second was the "next six months' domestic consumer
price" indicator, which rose 0.95 points from March to 39.45.
</P>
<P>
The "next six months' domestic economic outlook" indicator hit
51.80, up 0.40 points from the previous month, while the "next
six months' employment opportunities" indicator rose 0.35 points
to 74.90. The "next six months' family financial status"
indicator stood at 53.85, up 0.15 from the month-earlier level.
</P>
<P>
The only indicator that declined in April was the "timing for
buying durable goods over the next six months, " which dropped
0.70 points from March to 112.85.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by telephone April 19-21 among 2,349 adults
around Taiwan, has a margin of error of plus or minus 2 percent.
</P>
